\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 Point of View : Unified API Strategy using Layer 7\

\f1\b0 \
Key Assumptions :\
\
1. Broadcom Commercials  - Broadcom is known for increasing prices a lot\
[300-400%. Historical data ] - Exit cost will be really high after 3-4 years.\
2. Developer Friction - Layer 7 historically requires centralized gateway team. In today\'92s world we want federated and self (team/domain) managed model.\
3. Hybrid and Multi-cloud - Bank will have on-prem and multi-cloud setup for next decade. We are not going 100% cloud.\
\
The concern - Layer-7 as strategic API gateway.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 In a multi-cloud world, forcing Azure-native microservices to use a Layer7 "containerized" gateway adds a Java-heavy runtime, increased latency, and a proprietary policy language into a cloud-native ecosystem\
\
1. The GitOps and Automation Concern\
	"How does Layer7 v11.x integrate into a multi-cloud Terraform/Crossplane workflow without creating a 'Policy Silo'? Can a developer in the Azure team deploy an API and its security policy in a single 'git push' without waiting for a Layer7 admin?"\
	
\f3\b \strokec2 The Problem:
\f2\b0 \strokec2  Layer7's Graphman is a step forward, but it is still a proprietary abstraction.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\b \cf0 \strokec2 	The Solution:
\f2\b0  If Layer7 is chosen, mandate the implementation of an 
\f3\b API Abstraction Layer
\f2\b0 . Use a tool-agnostic specification (like 
\f3\b Backstage
\f2\b0  or a custom 
\f3\b OAS-to-Policy
\f2\b0  engine) that allows developers to define intent, which then auto-generates the Layer7 XML/JSON. 
\f4\i Don't let developers touch the 	Layer7 console.
\f2\i0 \
2. Cloud Compute cost \
	What is the memory and CPU footprint of a Layer7 gateway instance in AWS/Azure?At 10,000 requests per second, what is our projected 'Cloud Compute cost\'92  just to run the gateway?\
	The Problem : layer7 is a heavy gateway. Running it as a sidecar or distributed ingress in k8 is expensive and resource-intensive \
	
\f3\b The Solution:
\f2\b0  Implement a 
\f3\b Tiered Gateway Pattern
\f2\b0 .\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl1
\f3\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u8259 
\f3 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Tier 1 (The Edge):
\f2\b0  Use Azure APIM/AWS Gateway for commodity security (DDoS, Rate Limiting, WAF).\
\ls1\ilvl1
\f3\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u8259 
\f3 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Tier 2 (The Fortress):
\f2\b0  Use Layer7 only for "Crown Jewel" APIs that require deep legacy integration (e.g., Mainframe identity propagation, complex SOAP-to-REST).\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 3. AI and Modern protocol gap\
	As we move to AI-agentic banking, how does Layer7 handle 
\f3\b \strokec2 LLM-specific governance
\f2\b0 \strokec2  (e.g., token-based rate limiting, prompt injection filtering, or semantic caching)? Are we going to wait 24 months for a Broadcom patch, or build it ourselves in a tool not designed for it?\
	
\f3\b \strokec2 The Problem:
\f2\b0 \strokec2  Layer7 is reactive, not proactive, regarding modern protocols like gRPC or AI-specific traffic.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\b \cf0 \strokec2 	The Solution:
\f2\b0  Positioning Layer7 as a 
\f3\b "Security Sidecar"
\f2\b0  rather than the "Front Door." Use lightweight, extensible proxies for AI/Modern workloads and offload the "Audit/Compliance" logging to Layer7 via an asynchronous side-channel.\
\

